Human – Computer - Interaction
(cid:0) Human : a user, a group of users , or a sequence of users in
an organization, trying to get the job done with the
technology.
(cid:0) Computer: any tech. ranging from the general desktop to a
large-scale computer system.
(cid:0) Interaction: any communication between a computer and a
user, direct or indirect.
The important thing is the user is interacting with the computer in order to accomplish something.
What is HCI ?
(cid:0) ‘Human Computer Interaction’
is a discipline
concerned with
the design, evaluation and
implementation of interactive computing systems for
human use and with the study of major phenomena
surrounding them.
What is HCI ?
(cid:0) HCI is the study of how people interact with
computers and to what extent computers are or are
not developed for successful interaction with human
beings.
What is HCI ?
(cid:0) Human–computer
interaction
is the study of
interaction
between people (users) and computers.
(cid:0) It is often regarded as the intersection of computer science,
behavioural sciences, design and several other fields of
study.
(cid:0) Interaction between users and computers occurs at the user
interface (or simply interface), which includes both software and
hardware), for example, general-purpose computer peripherals and
large-scale mechanical systems, such as aircraft and power plants.
Why HCI ?
(cid:0) Bad Design’s are very common.
(cid:0) But it is not Universal, so it can be done better.
(cid:0) Economics: Machines used to be more valuable, now humans
are.
(cid:0) Potential for theoretical advances: theories of interaction.

Three ‘use’ words:
(cid:0) There are three ‘use’ words that must all be true for a
product to be successful; it must be:
(cid:0) useful – accomplish what is required: play music,
cook dinner, format a document;
(cid:0) usable – do it easily and naturally, without danger
of error, etc.;
(cid:0) used – make people want to use it, be attractive,
engaging, fun, etc.
Why HCI ?
(cid:0) Historically and with some exceptions, computer system developers
have not paid much attention to computer ease-of-use. Many
computer users today would argue that computer makers are still not
paying enough attention to making their products "user-friendly."
(cid:0) However, computer system developers might argue that computers are
extremely complex products to design and make and that the
demand for the services that computers can provide has always
outdriven the demand for ease-of-use.
Why HCI study is important?
(cid:0) One important HCI factor is that different users form different
conceptions or mental models about their interactions and have
different ways of learning and keeping knowledge and skills
(different "cognitive styles" as
in,
for example, "left-brained" and
"right-brained" people).
(cid:0) In addition, cultural and national differences play a part. Another
consideration in studying or designing HCI is that user interface
technology changes rapidly, offering new interaction possibilities
to which previous research findings may not apply. Finally, user preferences
change as they gradually master new interfaces.
Goal of HCI
(cid:0) A basic goal of HCI is to improve the interactions between users and
computers by making computers more usable and receptive to the user's
needs.
(cid:0) A long term goal of HCI is to design systems that minimize the
barrier between the human's cognitive model of what they want
to accomplish and the computer's understanding of the user's
task.

HCI is concerned with: (cid:0) Methodologies and processes for designing interfaces (i.e., given a task and a
class of users, design the best possible interface within given constraints, optimizing
for a desired property such as learning ability or efficiency of use).
(cid:0) Methods for implementing interfaces (e.g. software toolkits and libraries for
implementing interfaces (e.g. software toolkits and libraries; efficient algorithms) .
(cid:0) Techniques for evaluating and comparing interfaces .
(cid:0) Developing new interfaces and interaction techniques .
(cid:0) Developing descriptive and predictive models and theories of interaction.
Future of HCI (cid:0) Future of human-computer interaction is affected by the forces which in turn
change the shape of the nature of future computing. These forces include:
(cid:0) Decreasing hardware costs leading to larger memories and faster systems.
(cid:0) Miniaturization of hardware leading to portability.
(cid:0) Reduction in power requirements leading to portability.
(cid:0) Specialized hardware leading to new functions.
(cid:0) Increased development of network communication and distributed computing.
Future of HCI (cid:0) Increasingly widespread use of computers, especially by people who are
outside of the computing profession.
(cid:0) Increasing innovation in input techniques (e.g., voice, gesture, pen), combined
with lowering cost, leading to rapid computerization by people.
(cid:0) Wider social concerns leading to improved access to computers by special
group of people such as young children, the physically/visually disabled.

How People Do Things: The 7 Stages of Action
(cid:0) Forming a goal
(cid:0) example: I want more light so I can see better.
(cid:0) Forming the intention
(cid:0) example: I will turn on some lights.
(cid:0) Specifying an action
(cid:0) example: I will walk to the wall, and move the light switch up.
(cid:0) Executing the action
(cid:0) example: Attempting to do the action.
(cid:0) Perceiving the state of the world (Ex. Literature Survey)
(cid:0) example: I look around.
(cid:0) Interpreting the state of the world
(cid:0) example: Can I see better? (cid:0) Evaluating the outcome
(cid:0) example: If I can see better, I have succeeded!
How People Do Things: Sample (cid:0) Forming a goal: What do I want? (cid:0) Forming the intention: What would satisfy this
goal?
(cid:0) Specifying an action: What do I have to do to
achieve the intention?
(cid:0) Executing the action: Do the steps I have
specified.
(cid:0) Perceiving the state of the world: Use my senses to gather information about the world and/or system I am working with.
(cid:0) Interpreting the state of the world: Figure out
what, if anything, has changed.
(cid:0) Evaluating the outcome: Did I achieve my goal?

Memory: How do we remember?
(cid:0) Short Term Memory (STM)
(cid:0) How many numbers can you remember?
(cid:0) Humans can usually handle about 7 items of
information (±2, or 5–9) at once.
(cid:0) This doesn’t mean that 10 links is too many. It just
means that having more choices imposes a greater
burden on the user’s ability to process information.
(cid:0) We recall things from STM effortlessly.

Affordances
(cid:0) Using what we interact with a system? (cid:0) Affordances are parts of a system that allow (or
afford) us to interact with the system.
(cid:0) Buttons, scrollbars, the mouse, the keyboard, other
widgets, etc.
(cid:0) Anything we can interact with is an affordance.

Affordances are an object’s properties that show the possible actions users can take with it, thereby suggesting how they may interact with that object. For instance, a button can look as if it needs to be turned or pushed. The characteristics of the button which make it look “turnable” or “pushable” together form its affordances.

Constraints
Physical, Semantic, Cultural, Logical
Physical constraints
(cid:0) Physical limitations that constrain possible
actions (cid:0) Examples:
(cid:0) Jigsaw puzzle, where the pieces only fit together in one way. Here the physical constraints of the design guide the user to complete the task.
(cid:0) Cars that can’t start unless in neutral (cid:0) What physical constraints does the machine impose in terms of screen space, memory capacity and speed
Semantic constraints
(cid:0) When the meaning of a situation controls the
possible actions

(cid:0) Examples: (cid:0) For example, the function of a car is to transport people from a point to another. The car must be running on the road and the driver must be seated facing the front in order to see the road. The actions of driving the car on the road and sitting facing the front to operate a car would be considered as a semantic constraint. (cid:0) Why are you sitting where you are? (cid:0) Why are you facing forward?
(cid:0) What happens if the user doesn’t understand the
meaning/purpose of the system/situation?
Cultural constraints
(cid:0) Relies on accepted cultural conventions (cid:0) What does red mean?
(cid:0) stop, danger, alert
(cid:0) What does yellow mean? (cid:0) warning, slow, caution
(cid:0) Why might cultural constraints fail? (cid:0) Why use them at all?
(cid:0) Because a particular culture shares the same
knowledge and experience.
Logical constraints
(cid:0) Using logic to constrain actions (cid:0) Natural mappings (cid:0) left-right, up-down
(cid:0) Sequence
(cid:0) doing things in an obvious order (1,2,3 a,b,c)
(cid:0) Completeness
(cid:0) using all the parts, filling in all the fields, etc.

Principles of HCI (cid:0) When evaluating a current user interface, or designing a new user interface, it is important to keep in mind the following experimental design principles:

(cid:0) Early focus on user(s) and task(s): Establish how many users are needed to perform the task(s) and determine who the appropriate users should be; someone who has never used the interface, and will not use the interface in the future, is most likely not a valid user. In addition, define the task(s) the users will be performing and how often the task(s) need to be performed.
Principles of HCI

(cid:0) Empirical measurement: Test the interface early with real users who come in contact with the interface on a daily basis. Keep in mind that results may vary with the performance level of the user and may not be an accurate depiction of the typical Establish human–computer quantitative usability specifics such as: the number of users performing the task(s), the time to complete the task(s), and the number of errors made during the task(s).
interaction.
Principles of HCI

(cid:0) Iterative design: After determining the users, tasks, and empirical measurements to include, perform the following iterative design steps: (cid:0) Design the user interface (cid:0) Test (cid:0) Analyze results (cid:0) Repeat
Repeat the iterative design process until a sensible, user-friendly interface is created.
Principles of HCI
(cid:0) Learnability
(cid:0) The ease with which new users can begin effective
interaction and achieve maximal performance.
(cid:0) Flexibility
(cid:0) The multiplicity of ways the user and system
exchange information.
(cid:0) Robustness
(cid:0) The level of support provided to the user in and
determining assessment of goal directed behaviour.

(cid:0) Dialog initiative

(cid:0) Multi-threading
(cid:0) Provide support for simultaneous tasks.

(cid:0) Substitutability

Robustness
(cid:0) Observability
(cid:0) User should be able to evaluate the internal state of the

(cid:0) Recoverability
(cid:0) Support for undoing errors.
(cid:0) Responsiveness
(cid:0) Feedback should be commensurate with action.
(cid:0) Task conformance

Principles of user interface design

(cid:0) Seven principles of user interface design that may be considered at any time during the design of a user interface in any order: (cid:0) Tolerance, (cid:0) Simplicity, (cid:0) Visibility, (cid:0) Affordance, (cid:0) Consistency, (cid:0) Structure and (cid:0) Feedback.
User-centered design
(cid:0) User-centered design (UCD) is a modern, widely practiced design philosophy rooted in the idea that users must take center-stage in the design of any computer system.
(cid:0) Users, designers and technical practitioners work together to articulate the wants, needs and limitations of the user and create a system that addresses these elements.
